Also your code has following bug:

        List&lt;String&gt; allStrings = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
    
     // It throws IndexOutOfBoundsException!!!
        String shortest = allStrings.get(0);

Well there are a couple of problems here. If you ran your code, you would have gotten an `IndexOutOfBoundException` in `doIt()` because your `allStrings` list is empty and hence when you call `String shortest = allStrings.get(0);` your calling something that is not in your list. 

Also, the logic `if(s.length()&gt;shortest.length()))` is a bit odd as essentially you really only comparing the Strings in your List and not against what you have read from the file. Hence you&#39;ll never determine if the line you&#39;ve read from the file is *smaller* than any of the lines you already have. 

Finally, this code ... `for (String text: allStrings) {w.println(text); }` ... to write your file is in the loop, hence your writing the String each loop iteration. 

You don&#39;t need the *shortest* variable, just use a boolean to indicate if the string you&#39;ve read in is shorter than those already in your list and only if it is, add it to your list. 

    public static void doIt(BufferedReader r, PrintWriter w) throws IOException {
        List&lt;String&gt; shortestStrings = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();

        String line = r.readLine();
        shortestStrings.add(line);

        while(line != null) {
            boolean isShortert = Boolean.TRUE;
            for(String s: shortestStrings) {
                if(line.length() &gt; s.length()) {
                    isShortert = Boolean.FALSE;
                }
            }
            if(isShortert) {
                shortestStrings.add(line);
            }
            line = r.readLine();
        }

        for (String text: shortestStrings) {
            w.println(text);
        }
    }

